San Jacinto College awards college credit for certain CLEP exams.

The College-Level Examination Program (CLEP) offers students the opportunity to receive college credit for what they already know.
Most exams are timed at 90-minutes except for the College Composition exam (2 hours).
The cost of each CLEP exam is $87 each and there is also a $20 administrative fee (non-refundable) assessed for each test date.
There is a $10 fee for all test takers that are taking an optional essay.

For more information about registering for CLEP, including which CLEP exams are offered, click: CLEP Information

Do a Graduation Status Check. Log into SOS and go to Student Records, run a degree evaluation and print it out. Write in notes next to requirements that are currently in progress or pending, and bring the form to the EPCC office on the campus where you would like to graduate by the deadline listed in the class schedule.

Step 3: Maintain Financial Aid Appeal Contract Requirements

As stated in your appeal contract, while on financial aid appeal, your conditions are as follows:
Pass all classes with a minimum of letter grade C.
You may not withdraw or drop courses while on financial aid appeal
You may not change your major, or take courses not listed on the degree plan filed with the financial aid appeal
Complete literacy and coaching Program for Financial Education (PFE) component

Step 2: Complete Financial Literacy Component

You are required to attend one financial literacy workshop on campus or complete five financial literacy modules in Blackboard.

Click the link Campus Workshops to open a list of the campus workshops. You are welcome to attend any on campus financial literacy session. No appointment is needed. Please arrive early, as max attendance is limited to 60 students.
Please use the following link to review instructions on how to enroll and navigate in the Program for Financial Education Blackboard course under the Online Course in Blackboard section: Financial Aid PFE

Step 1: Schedule PFE Coaching

For fall and spring appeals, you are required to meet with the PFE coach in the Educational Planning and Counseling Center at least twice per term. For summer appeals, you are required to meet with the PFE coach in the Educational Planning and Counseling Center at least once per term. You will have four weeks from the end of your first term of appeal to meet with your PFE coach. If you miss this deadline, you will be required to wait until two weeks after the beginning of your next term of enrollment to complete this requirement.

To schedule your PFE appointment, you can go in person to the campus Educational Planning, Counseling, & Completion Office to get a contact card. Once received, you will set it up via the contact person on the card. Or, you may call 281-998-6150 to speak with the Educational Planning, Counseling, & Completion Office to schedule.

5. Pay for Classes.
Dual Credit at San Jacinto College is affordable. You pay only 25% of tuition and fees for certain classes that count toward both high school and college, and you may even be covered for that amount if you qualify for the Texas Public Education Grant (TPEG). Check with your high school counselor, the Dual Credit Office, or SJC Financial Aid for more information.
o To remain in your classes, you must pay your portion of tuition and fees by the college's posted deadline. Some schools cover these costs for students. Check with your counselor for further information.
o Once a student has been registered, they will be given the 75% fee waiver if applicable to be taken to the Business Office. The remaining balance is due immediately to avoid being dropped from classes. Payment Plans are available.
o Financial Aid - If you're in high school and enroll in dual credit classes, you may apply for a TPEG to cover your share of the tuition and fees. You must complete the TASFA or a paper version of the FAFSA and submit income documents along with your TPEG dual credit application at one of our campus Financial Aid Offices

You will only see the SERA once each academic year. San Jac's academic year runs from September 1st through August 31st.

So for example, if you register for Summer clasees and on the same day or later, register for Fall classes, you will have separate agreements for each academic year and will not see the SERA until the next academic year.

As stated earlier, students must accept the SERA in order to register for classes at San Jacinto College. Those students that do not accept the SERA will not be able to register.

Friday, February 7th for Non-Credit classes.
Monday, February 24th for Credit classes for Summer 2020.
Monday, April 6th for Credit classes for Fall 2020.

Academic Plan

If you completed and met the conditions of the appeal during the probation term, but you still aren't making satisfactory academic progress, you will be placed on Academic Plan. While on Academic Plan, you must continue to meet the conditions of your appeal within a specific point in time as stated on your appeal packet.

Probation

If you failed to make satisfactory academic progress and you have appealed to have your financial aid reinstated, you are placed on Probation for one term. You are required to meet the conditions stated on your appeal approval contract without exception.

Suspension

If youre not in compliance by the end of your warning term or we receive transfer work while you are on a warning that does not improve your status, you will be placed on suspension and are no longer eligible to receive financial aid. There are still options for you to regain eligibility through the appeal process.

Maximum Time Frame

If you have attempted more than 90 hours (including transfer hours), you are no longer eligible to receive aid. There are still options for you to regain eligibility through the appeal process.

Warning

If for any reason you havent met the GPA or pass rate standards, you will be placed on financial aid warning. On warning status, you can continue to receive your financial aid.

Credit by Examination

Please Note: Each college and university has its own policy for credit earned by examination and any such credit allowed by one institution may not necessarily be accepted at another.

A student must have earned at least three credit hours of course work at San Jacinto College before the College will post credit for College Level Evaluation Program (CLEP), Advanced Placement (AP), International Baccalaureate (IB) or departmental examinations to the students transcript. Credit for CLEP, AP, IB, departmental examinations or a combination thereof may not exceed 30 credit hours.

A student who has previously received a grade (A, B, C, D, F or I) in a course may not receive CLEP, AP, IB, or departmental examination credit for the same course. Grades and credit hours are assigned to credit earned by departmental examinations; a minimum grade of C is required to earn credit. Term hours only are assigned to credit earned by CLEP, AP, and IB examinations. Residence credit is not given for CLEP, AP, IB or departmental examinations and they are not included in GPA calculations.

TASFA stands for the Texas Application for State Financial Aid. Students that are classified as a Texas Resident, and went to high school for at least three years in the state who cannot apply for federal financial aid using the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA) are encouraged to complete the TASFA. dialog_nodes.title: Installment Payment Plan Information

values.text:
Installment Payment Plans are available for the Fall, Spring and Summer semesters.

You can set up a payment plan online or at any campus business office. Depending on the length of the payment plan, you must pay the required down payment (range from 20% to 50%) in order to set up the payment plan. A \$25 service fee is also prorated over all installments, and theres a \$25 fee if there are any late payments.

Any classes added to a schedule while enrolled in a payment plan will be included in the plan automatically. The system will update and reflect the new payment plan amounts due before the next payment is scheduled.

dialog_nodes.title: Class Drops

values.text:
Oh no :(... We would hate to see you go! Drop Deadline Dates can be found here.

To drop a course online:
1. Go to the SOS login
2. To login: enter your Student ID number (capital G with the assigned eight digit number).
3. Enter your SOS password.
4. Select My Registration and follow the system prompts.
5. Select your desired registration term.
6. Select Step 5, Register for Classes, and select drop for desired classes under drop down box.
7. Select Submit Changes to save the request or to determine if there are registration restrictions.
8. When the schedule is correct, select the View My Schedule link at the bottom of the page to confirm your action.
